Lecture 2: Allama Iqbal & Quaid-e-Azam's Vision of Pakistan. Allama Iqbal, the national poet-philosopher, presented the concept of a separate Muslim state in his famous Allahabad Address of 1930. He envisioned a homeland where Muslims could develop their spiritual and cultural life. Quaid-e-Azam Muhammad Ali Jinnah, the founder of Pakistan, translated this vision into reality through his political leadership. Jinnah's vision of Pakistan was a democratic state based on Islamic principles of social justice, equality, and protection of minority rights, as articulated in his August 11, 1947 speech.